		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_586673"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				It is almost too babied. I mean locking MOBs. I can see the usefulness and why it was implemented based on griefing, training and KSing in EQ 1, but it almost feels too contrived, gamey. That's really not real. That kills some of the magic for me. Well it's quite obvious I'm not fully emersed in this fantasy world when I can't go do anything I'd like
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
While I can understand the contrived feeling, I do agree with the implementation of locked encounters.  In the big picture it allows the Dev's to balance content much easier.  Without locked encounters, we'll be back to powerlevelling, zerging, KSing, Training...these are NOT good things for any game and while EQ2 may have been a hardline solution it most certainly removes these bad elements and while it may be nice exploiting the non locked mob loopholes in EQ1, it's just not fun in the long run.<br />
<br />
I love the fact that you can't single pull groups of mobs anymore and if 8 are linked, you have to fight 8 all at once...it's SO much more fun than waiting for the monk to split, doing one at a time and then breaking the spawn so you can do 1 at a time all night.  Do you remember how boring that was?  It led to sony having to design content with the knowledge that every mob is going to be single pulled, so they do insane DPS, so you get mobs in Plane of Fire hitting harder than half the end game bosses of the expansion a year earlier. <br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				Even instanced zones once again I can see the usefulness, especially with the two city start point that creates blocks, but I think something was taken away by making everything instanced raids. Its like the MOBs no longer have souls, they are no longer individuals, or prized trophies that only spawn every so often if you will. Now two people can get the same loot off the same named MOB at the same time. You can no longer walk out of a Vox raid and say to yourself, I am the noly one who will have this spear for 5 days on the whole damn server. This for some reason takes away from a big part of the game for me and most others that focuses on your individual achievements.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
I agree with the instanced thing but it's a necessary evil.  Fighting over spawns having to race other guilds to content was not healthy for the game.  Instances in EQ2 are much less anyway so I think this issue isn't as bad as it's made out to be.  Much content is dynamically instanced so there is still competition for many things yet controlled enough to not have nothing to do.  If everything was instanced everywhere all the time It would suck too.  LDoN was a major turnoff for me this way.  Worst expansion EVER (to me anyway).<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				Harvesting tradeskill items.. once again the items just randomly appearing in the desert. Oh look, there is a rock outcropping next to a shrubbery and some roots. Its like the EQ Gods are sprinkling skittles for us to harvest. Doesnt feel quite right.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
I dunno I like this too...foraging in EQ1 certainly wasn't any better and only a select few classes could use. Neither was getting rare drops from mobs all the time...call me crazy but I think it makes way more sense to harvest resources instead of raw ore dropping from a mob's corpse...</div>
